[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] The **`Location`** interface represents the location (URL) of the object it is linked to.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Changes done on it are reflected on the object it relates to.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Both the `Document` and `Window` interface have such a linked `Location`, accessible via `Document.location` and `Window.location` respectively.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A static `DOMStringList` containing, in reverse order, the origins of all ancestor browsing contexts of the document associated with the given `Location` object.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A stringifier that returns a string containing the entire URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] If changed, the associated document navigates to the new page.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] It can be set from a different origin than the associated document.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final `':'`.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing the host, that is the *hostname*, a `':'`, and the *port* of the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing the domain of the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing the port number of the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing an initial `'/'` followed by the path of the URL, not including the query string or fragment.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing a `'?'` followed by the parameters or "query string" of the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Modern browsers provide `URLSearchParams` and `URL.searchParams` to make it easy to parse out the parameters from the query string.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] A string containing a `'#'` followed by the fragment identifier of the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Returns a string containing the canonical form of the origin of the specific location.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Loads the resource at the URL provided in parameter.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Reloads the current URL, like the Refresh button.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Replaces the current resource with the one at the provided URL (redirects to the provided URL).
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] The difference from the `assign()` method and setting the `href` property is that after using `replace()` the current page will not be saved in session `History`, meaning the user won't be able to use the *back* button to navigate to it.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] Returns a string containing the whole URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-location] It is a synonym for `Location.href`, though it can't be used to modify the value.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] The **`URL`** interface is used to parse, construct, normalize, and encode URLs.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] It works by providing properties which allow you to easily read and modify the components of a URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] You normally create a new `URL` object by specifying the URL as a string when calling its constructor, or by providing a relative URL and a base URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] You can then easily read the parsed components of the URL or make changes to the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Creates and returns a `URL` object from a URL string and optional base URL string.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Throws if the passed arguments don't define a valid URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] A string containing the domain (that is the *hostname*) followed by (if a port was specified) a `':'` and the *port* of the URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] A stringifier that returns a string containing the whole URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Returns a string containing the origin of the URL, that is its scheme, its domain and its port.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] A string containing the password specified before the domain name.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] A string indicating the URL's parameter string; if any parameters are provided, this string includes all of them, beginning with the leading `?` character.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] A `URLSearchParams` object which can be used to access the individual query parameters found in `search`.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] A string containing the username specified before the domain name.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Returns a boolean indicating whether or not a URL defined from a URL string and optional base URL string is parsable and valid.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Returns a string containing a unique blob URL, that is a URL with `blob:` as its scheme, followed by an opaque string uniquely identifying the object in the browser.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Creates and returns a `URL` object from a URL string and optional base URL string, or returns `null` if the passed parameters define an invalid `URL`.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Revokes an object URL previously created using `URL.createObjectURL()`.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] It is a synonym for `URL.href`, though it can't be used to modify the value.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] It returns the same string as the `href` property.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] The constructor takes a `url` parameter, and an optional `base` parameter to use as a base if the `url` parameter is a relative URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] Note that in the case below "dogs" is the filename segment (because it has no trailing slash), and the relative URL "cats" is interpreted relative to the *directory* part of the base URL, which is `http://www.example.com/animals/`.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] See Resolving relative references to a URL for more information.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] The constructor will raise an exception if the URL cannot be parsed to a valid URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] URLs are encoded according to the rules found in RFC 3986.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] The `URLSearchParams` interface can be used to build and manipulate the URL query string.
[src:same-origin-policy/api-url] The `toString()` method of `URL` just returns the value of the `href` property, so the constructor can be used to normalize and encode a URL directly.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] The **`domain`** property of the `Document` interface gets/sets the domain portion of the origin of the current document, as used by the same-origin policy.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] The document is forbidden from setting its domain, for example it is sandboxed or has an opaque origin.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] For code running at the URL `https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web`, this example would set `currentDomain` to the string `"developer.mozilla.org"`.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] The getter for this property returns the domain portion of the current document's origin.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] In most cases, this will be the hostname portion of the document's URL.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Although the getter is not dangerous in the same way that the setter is, it is likely simpler and more useful to use the `Location.hostname` property instead.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] For the URL `https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web`, `currentHostname` is also the string `"developer.mozilla.org"`.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Other alternatives that provide slightly different information are `Location.host`, which includes the port, and `Window.origin`, which provides the full origin.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] The setter for this property can be used to *change* a page's origin, and thus modify how certain security checks are performed.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] It can only be set to the same or a parent domain.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] then they have both modified their origin to have the same domain, and they can now access each other's DOM directly—despite being cross-origin, which would normally prevent such access.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Note that setting `document.domain` to its current value is not a no-op.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] then it will be counted as cross-origin from any other normally-same-origin pages that have not done the same thing.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] The `document.domain` setter is deprecated.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] It undermines the security protections provided by the same origin policy, and complicates the origin model in browsers, leading to interoperability problems and security bugs.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Attempting to set `document.domain` is dangerous.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] It opens up full access to a page's DOM from *all* subdomains, which is likely not what is intended.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] It also removes the port component from the origin, so now your page can be accessed by other pages with the same IP address or same host component, even on a different port.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] This is especially insecure on shared hosting.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] For example, another shared hosting customer is able to host a site at the same IP address but on a different port, then setting `document.domain` will remove the same-origin protection that normally protects you from that other customer's site accessing your site's data.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Similar problems occur with shared hosting sites that give each customer a different subdomain.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] If a site sets `document.domain`, any other customer on a different subdomain can now do the same thing, and start accessing the data of the original site.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Instead of using `document.domain` to facilitate cross-origin communication, you should use `Window.postMessage` to send an asynchronous message to the other origin.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] This controlled access via message-passing is much more secure than the blanket exposure of all data caused by `document.domain`.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] As an example of this last failure case, trying to set `document.domain` to `"example.org"` when on `https://example.com/` will throw.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Finally, setting `document.domain` does not change the origin used for origin-checks by some Web APIs, preventing sub-domain access via this mechanism.
[src:same-origin-policy/document-domain] Affected APIs include (but are not limited to): `Window.localStorage`, IndexDB API, `BroadcastChannel`, `SharedWorker`.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] Web content's **origin** is defined by the *scheme* (protocol), *hostname* (domain), and *port* of the URL used to access it.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] Two objects have the same origin only when the scheme, hostname, and port all match.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] Some operations are restricted to same-origin content, and this restriction can be lifted using CORS.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] An opaque origin is a special type of browser-internal value that obscures the true origin of a resource (opaque origins are always serialized as `null`).
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] They are used by the browser to ensure resource isolation as they are never considered equal to any other origin — including other opaque origins.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] Opaque origins are applied in cases where the true origin of a resource is sensitive, cannot be safely used for security checks, or does not exist.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] A resource with an opaque origin will have its `Origin` HTTP header in requests set to `null`.
[src:same-origin-policy/glossary-origin] It will also fail same-origin checks with any other resource, and hence be restricted to only those operations available to cross-origin resources.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] In computing, the **same-origin policy** (**SOP**) is a concept in the web application security model.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Under the policy, a web browser permits scripts contained in a first web page to access data in a second web page, but only if both web pages have the same *origin*.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] An origin is defined as a combination of URI scheme, host name, and port number.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This policy prevents a malicious script on one page from obtaining access to sensitive data on another web page through that page's Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This mechanism bears a particular significance for modern web applications that extensively depend on HTTPS cookies to maintain authenticated user sessions, as servers act based on the HTTP cookie information to reveal sensitive information or perform state-changing actions.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] A strict separation between content provided by unrelated sites must be maintained on the client-side to prevent the loss of data confidentiality or integrity.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy applies only to scripts.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This means that resources such as images, CSS, and dynamically loaded scripts can be accessed across origins via the corresponding HTML tags (with fonts being a notable exception).
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Attacks take advantage of the fact that the same origin policy does not apply to HTML tags.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] There are some mechanisms available to relax the SOP; one of them is cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The concept of same-origin policy was introduced by Netscape Navigator 2.02 in 1995, shortly after the introduction of JavaScript in Netscape 2.0.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] JavaScript enabled scripting on web pages, and in particular programmatic access to the DOM.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The policy was originally designed to protect access to the DOM, but has since been broadened to protect sensitive parts of the global JavaScript object.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] All modern browsers implement some form of the same-origin policy as it is an important security cornerstone.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The algorithm used to calculate the "origin" of a URI is specified in RFC 6454, Section 4.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] For absolute URIs, the origin is the triple {scheme, host, port}.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] If the URI does not use a hierarchical element as a naming authority (see RFC 3986, Section 3.2) or if the URI is not an absolute URI, then a globally unique identifier is used.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Two resources are considered to be of the same origin if and only if all these values are exactly the same.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] To illustrate, the following table gives an overview of typical outcomes for checks against the URL "**http://www.example.com/dir/page.html**".
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Unlike other browsers, Internet Explorer does not include the port in the calculation of the origin, using the Security Zone in its place.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy protects against reusing authenticated sessions across origins.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The following example illustrates a potential security risk that could arise without the same-origin policy.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Assume that a user is visiting a banking website and doesn't log out.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Then, the user goes to another site that has malicious JavaScript code that requests data from the banking site.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Because the user is still logged in on the banking site, the malicious code could do anything the user could do on the banking site.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] For example, it could get a list of the user's last transactions, create a new transaction, etc.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This is because, in the original spirit of a World Wide Web, browsers are required to tag along authentication details such as session cookies and platform-level kinds of the Authorization request header to the banking site based on the domain of the banking site.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The bank site owners would expect that regular browsers of users visiting the malicious site do not allow the code loaded from the malicious site access the banking session cookie or platform-level authorization.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] While it is true that JavaScript has no direct access to the banking session cookie, it could still send and receive requests to the banking site with the banking site's session cookie.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Same Origin Policy was introduced as a requirement for security-minded browsers to deny read access to responses from across origins, with the assumption that the majority of users choose to use compliant browsers.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Counteracting the abuse of the write permission requires additional CSRF protections by the target sites.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] In some circumstances, the same-origin policy is too restrictive, posing problems for large websites that use multiple subdomains.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] At first, a number of workarounds such as using the fragment identifier or the `window.name` property were used to pass data between documents residing in different domains.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Netscape Navigator briefly contained a taint checking feature.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The feature was experimentally introduced in 1997 as part of Netscape 3.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The feature was turned off by default, but if enabled by a user it would allow websites to attempt to read JavaScript properties of windows and frames belonging to a different domain.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The browser would then ask the user whether to permit the access in question.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] If two windows (or frames) contain scripts that set domain to the same value, the same-origin policy is relaxed for these two windows, and each window can interact with the other.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] For example, cooperating scripts in documents loaded from orders.example.com and catalog.example.com might set their `document.domain` properties to “example.com”, thereby making the documents appear to have the same origin and enabling each document to read properties of the other.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Setting this property implicitly sets the port to null, which most browsers will interpret differently from port 80 or even an unspecified port.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] To assure that access will be allowed by the browser, set the document.domain property of both pages.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The `document.domain` concept was introduced as part of Netscape Navigator 3, released in 1996.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The other technique for relaxing the same-origin policy is standardized under the name cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This standard extends HTTP with a new `Origin` request header and a new `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] It allows servers to use a header to explicitly list origins that may request a file or to use a wildcard and allow a file to be requested by any site.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Browsers such as Firefox 3.5, Safari 4 and Internet Explorer 10 use this header to allow the cross-origin HTTP requests with XMLHttpRequest that would otherwise have been forbidden by the same-origin policy.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Another technique, cross-document messaging, allows a script from one page to pass textual messages to a script on another page regardless of the script origins.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Calling the postMessage() method on a Window object asynchronously fires an "onmessage" event in that window, triggering any user-defined event handlers.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] A script in one page still cannot directly access methods or variables in the other page, but they can communicate safely through this message-passing technique.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Since HTML `<script>` elements are allowed to retrieve and execute content from other domains, a page can bypass the same-origin policy and receive JSON data from a different domain by loading a resource that returns a JSONP payload.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] JSONP payloads consist of an internal JSON payload wrapped by a pre-defined function call.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] When the script resource is loaded by the browser, the designated callback function will be invoked to process the wrapped JSON payload.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Modern browsers will permit a script to connect to a WebSocket address without applying the same-origin policy.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] However, they recognize when a WebSocket URI is used, and insert an **Origin:** header into the request that indicates the origin of the script requesting the connection.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] To ensure cross-site security, the WebSocket server must verify that that origin is permitted to receive a reply.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The behavior of same-origin checks and related mechanisms is not well-defined in a number of corner cases such as for pseudo-protocols that do not have a clearly defined host name or port associated with their URLs (file:, data:, etc.).
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This historically caused a fair number of security problems, such as the generally undesirable ability of any locally stored HTML file to access all other files on the disk, or communicate with any site on the Internet.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Lastly, certain types of attacks, such as DNS rebinding or server-side proxies, permit the host name check to be partly subverted, and make it possible for rogue web pages to directly interact with sites through addresses other than their "true", canonical origin.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The impact of such attacks is limited to very specific scenarios, since the browser still believes that it is interacting with the attacker's site, and therefore does not disclose third-party cookies or other sensitive information to the attacker.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Even when same-origin policy is in effect (without being relaxed by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), certain cross-origin attacks can be performed.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] WebRTC can be used to find out the internal IP address of a victim.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] If attempting to connect to a cross-origin port, responses cannot be read in face of same-origin policy, but a JavaScript can still make inferences on whether the port is open or closed by checking if the onload/onerror event fires, or if we get a timeout.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This gives opportunities for cross-origin portscanning.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Further, JavaScript snippets can use techniques like cross-site leaks to exploit long-standing information leakages in the browser to infer information cross-origin.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] These attacks can be counteracted by implementing a Cross-Origin Resource Policy (CORP) header, which allows a website owner to block cross-origin or cross-site resources, like images, videos, and stylesheets.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] CORP can also block JavaScript-initiated `fetch` requests, but only if they are sent with the `no-cors` request mode.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy does not prevent the browser from making GET, POST, OPTIONS, and TRACE requests; it only prevents the responses from being read by user code.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Therefore, if an endpoint uses one of these "safe" request methods to write information or perform an action on a user's behalf, it can be exploited by attackers.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Note that the same-origin policy does not apply to cookies for historical reasons.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] If multiple adversarial sites are deployed on the same hostname with different port numbers, contrary to the SOP, all cookies set by any of the sites are shared.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] This can be used to leak users' session tokens and steal account information.
[src:same-origin-policy/same-origin-policy] Therefore, web services should be separated by differentiating subdomains rather than port numbers.
[src:same-origin-policy/window-origin] The **`origin`** read-only property of the `Window` interface returns the origin of the global scope, serialized as a string.
[src:same-origin-policy/window-origin] Executed from inside window scope, the following snippet will log the document's global scope's origin to the console.
[src:same-origin-policy/window-origin] If the origin is not a scheme/host/port tuple (say you are trying to run it locally, i.e., via `file://` URL), `origin` will return the string `"null"`.
